I'm sure we'll see some really good implementations in other languages. The PDS has a relatively simple job in the atproto architecture, which will lend itself to rewrites and hyper-optimization.

Like most big technical changes, the PDS moving from a monolithic Postgres instance to per user SQLite database has trade-offs. It won't be pure win, but it should be a huge net win.

An open question is whether litestream.io will work for this use-case. If not, we'll be doing a lot of snapshotting.

images.alt: As a heads up of a particularly disruptive upcoming change, we are likely going to drop support for postgresql for the reference PDS, and instead move to a data storage model where each repo has a separate sqlite file on disk. We are not planning to provide a clean migration path or script or documentation for the delicate cut-over this will require.

As a heads up of a particularly disruptive upcoming change, we are likely going to drop support for postgresql for the reference PDS, and instead move to a data storage model where each repo has a separate sqlite file on disk. We are not planning to provide a clean migration path or script or documentation for the delicate cut-over this will require.

record.text: Maybe some day we'll see how a PDS running in Erlang or something will run. Pleroma is a lightweight ActityPub thing written in Elixir (which runs on the Erlang VM) and reportedly performs well, pleroma.social
